# NO BYTE-IDENTITY SEAL AT B5 — BY DESIGN.
#
# gcc-15.2.0-glibc is the "self-hosting fixed point" (buildplan B5).  It is built by R12
# (stage0-gcc-15.2.0, a DIFFERENT — musl-linked — compiler) targeting the from-source glibc-2.42.
# A different compiler produces different bytes, so byte-identity to the debian PREBUILT gcc is
# EXPLICITLY NOT expected (b4-b7-readiness risk #3).  There is therefore NO `sha256sum -c` gate at
# the tail of build.sh (unlike the sealed stage0-* rungs).
#
# The correctness invariant B5 DOES enforce is the fail-shut FUNCTIONAL gate in build.sh:
#   - cross-DSO C++ exception handling through the fresh libgcc_s.so.1 (the check B4 deferred);
#   - backtrace(3) against the fresh glibc + libgcc_s unwinder;
#   - long-double / %.17g / %a printf (the R4 fmt_fp silent-corruption class);
#   - __thread TLS across two translation units.
#
# The DETERMINISM proof for these leaves is B6 (differential-coreutils: compile twice — prebuilt vs
# bedrock toolchain — and byte-diff, aided by -ffile-prefix-map + --build-id=none).  The
# SELF-HOSTING fixed point is proved by having this glibc-linked gcc rebuild ITSELF to a stable
# result, NOT by parity with the prebuilt.
#
# Pin nothing here.  If a future policy wants a self-consistency anchor, capture the shas of the
# deliverable drivers + shared runtime libs from the SECOND (self-hosted) build, not the first:
# <sha>  usr/bin/gcc
# <sha>  usr/bin/g++
# <sha>  usr/lib/libstdc++.so.6.0.34
# <sha>  usr/lib/libgcc_s.so.1
